    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-05-19T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-05-19T15:00:00-05:00" n="94"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d94">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 703.72/4799a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d94fn1">The same, <hi rend="italic">mutatis
                            mutandis</hi>, on the same date, to the Ambassador in France (No. 2272),
                        referring to entry into France.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-05-19T15:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 19, 1917, 3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4853. Major <persName corresp="#p_PGJJ1">General Pershing</persName>, Commander
                    American expedition, accompanied by staff and headquarters, numbering altogether
                    about 150 persons, will sail on the <hi rend="italic">Baltic</hi> on May 24<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d94fn2">By telegram No. 4868, May 24, the date of sailing was
                        changed to May 28. (File No. 763.72/4815.)</note> for England <hi
                        rend="italic">en route</hi> to France. Make arrangements to facilitate entry
                    and passage through England. Officers and soldiers in uniform will not <pb
                        facs="0141" n="67" xml:id="pg_67"/> be provided with passports. Civilian
                    employees will be provided with certificates of identification issued by the War
                    Department, with photographs attached. Please ascertain and telegraph Department
                    as soon as possible whether this arrangement will be satisfactory, as to this
                    particular party and as to members of expeditionary forces who may pass through
                    England hereafter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
